<doc id="221408" wikidata="Q1379808" url="?curid=221408" title="Pierre-Louis GinguenÃ©">
<text>Pierre-Louis GinguenÃ© (25 April 1748 â 16 November 1816) was a French author.

==Biography==
He was born at Rennes, in Brittany, and educated at a Jesuit college there. He came to Paris in 1772, and wrote criticisms for the &quot;Mercure de France&quot;. He also composed a comic opera, &quot;Pomponin&quot; (1777). The &quot;Satire des satires&quot; (1778) and the &quot;Confession de ZulmÃ©&quot; (1779) followed. The &quot;Confession&quot; was claimed by several different authors and was very successful.

GinguenÃ©&#x27;s defence of Niccola Piccinni against the partisans of Gluck made him more widely known. He hailed the first symptoms of the French Revolution, and joined Giuseppe Cerutti, the author of the &quot;MÃ©moire pour le peuple franÃ§ais&quot; (1788), and others in producing the &quot;Feuille villageoise&quot;, a weekly paper addressed to the villages of France. He also celebrated in an indifferent ode the opening of the states-general. In his &quot;Lettres sur les confessions de J.-J. Rousseau&quot; (1791), he defended the life and principles of his author.

He was imprisoned during the Reign of Terror and escaped with life only by the downfall of Maximilien Robespierre. After his release he assisted, as director-general of the &quot;commission exÃ©cutive de l&#x27;instruction publique&quot;, in reorganizing the system of public instruction, and he was an original member of the Institute of France. In 1797, the Directory appointed him minister plenipotentiary to the king of Sardinia. After seven months, GinguenÃ© retired to his country house of St Prix, in the valley of Montmorency. He was appointed a member of the tribunate, but Napoleon, finding that he was not sufficiently tractable, had him expelled at the first &quot;purge&quot;, and GinguenÃ© returned to his literary pursuits.

== Career ==
He was one of the commission appointed to continue the &quot;Histoire littÃ©raire de la France&quot;, and he contributed to the volumes of this series which appeared in 1814, 1817 and 1820. GinguenÃ©&#x27;s most important work is the &quot;Histoire littÃ©raire d&#x27;Italie&quot; (14 vols., 1811â1835). He was putting the finishing touches to the eighth and ninth volumes when he died. The last five volumes were written by Francesco Salfi and revised by Pierre Daunou.

In the composition of his history of Italian literature he was guided for the most part by the great work of Girolamo Tiraboschi, but he avoids the prejudices and party views of his model.

GinguenÃ© edited the &quot;DÃ©cade philosophique, politique et littÃ©raire&quot; until it was suppressed by Napoleon in 1807. He contributed largely to the &quot;Biographie universelle&quot;, the &quot;Mercure de France&quot; and the &quot;Encyclopidie mÃ©thodique&quot;; and he edited the works of Nicolas Chamfort and of Lebrun. Among his minor productions are an opera, &quot;Pomponin on le tuteur mystifiÃ©&quot; (1777); &quot;La Satire des satires&quot; (1778); &quot;De l&#x27;autoritÃ© de Rabelais dans la revolution prÃ©sente&quot; (1791); &quot;De M. Neckar&quot; (1795); &quot;Fables nouvelles&quot; (1810); &quot;Fables inÃ©dites&quot; (1814).

==Legacy==
GinguenÃ© is buried in the PÃ¨re-Lachaise cemetery in Paris.

The Rue GinguenÃ© in Rennes is named after him.

